In contrast, unlike the western Palaearctic Zygaeninae (Burnet moths) and Procridinae (Forester moths, Smoky moths), which have been the subject of frequent and close study (e.g. Ebert, 1994 ; Guenin, 1997 ; Efetov & Tarmann, 1999 ;
Naumann et al ., 1999
, De Freina & Witt, 2001 ), most of the previous studies dealing with the Chalcosiinae have restricted themselves to establishing new taxa and carrying out faunistic surveys.
